    <TD dir=3Dltr oncopy=3D"e++; SetFirst('5');" width=3D"100%">
      <DIV=20
      style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 15px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; PADDING-BOTTOM: =
0px; PADDING-TOP: 0px">
      <H1>Interoperability Principles</H1>
      <H2 class=3Dsubtitle>Open Connections, Standards Support, Data=20
      Portability</H2>
      <DIV class=3Ddate>Published: February 21, 2008<SPAN =
class=3DdatePipe> |=20
      </SPAN>Updated: February 21, 2008</DIV>
      <DIV style=3D"HEIGHT: 18px"></DIV>
      <P>Microsoft recognizes that in an increasingly interconnected =
computing=20
      landscape, enabling interoperability between products from =
different=20
      vendors has become more important than ever. Spurred in part by =
the=20
      standards-based nature of the Internet, the computing industry has =
made=20
      great strides toward achieving effective interoperability between =
a wide=20
      range of products to meet customer needs. But customers are =
demanding more=20
      from all software companies. </P>
      <P>For its part, Microsoft recognizes the important =
responsibilities that=20
      it bears by virtue of the mission-critical use of its products by=20
      customers worldwide on a daily basis. Certain Microsoft products =
(Windows=20
      Vista including the .NET Framework, Windows Server 2008, SQL =
Server 2008,=20
      Office 2007, Exchange 2007, and Office SharePoint Server 2007, and =
future=20
      versions of these products, referred to in this document as =
=93high-volume=20
      products=94) have become so central to operational continuity of =
customers=92=20
      businesses that interoperability and data portability solutions =
are more=20
      valued than ever. To promote such interoperability and ensure the=20
      continued appeal of its products to developers and customers, =
Microsoft is=20
      committed to designing these high-volume products, and to running =
its=20
      business, in accordance with the following principles addressed to =
open=20
      connections to its products, support for industry standards and =
data=20
      portability. </P>
      <P>To guide Microsoft in its work under these principles, =
Microsoft will=20
      rely on input from the Interoperability Executive Customer =
Council, a=20
      customer advisory council consisting mainly of Chief Information =
Officers=20
      and Chief Technology Officers of large enterprises and government=20
      departments from around the world. In addition to other sources of =

      community and customer input, the Council will provide important =
direction=20
      to Microsoft concerning matters such as which new or updated =
standards are=20
      most important for implementation in Microsoft=92s products and =
how best to=20
      ensure interoperability in scenarios where existing industry=20
      implementations of a standard may subtly vary from one another. =
</P>
      <P><B>Principle I: Open Connections to Microsoft =
Products</B><BR>Microsoft=20
      is committed to establishing and maintaining open connections =
between its=20
      high-volume products and non-Microsoft products. There are two =
ways that=20
      products generally interoperate with one another: through external =

      protocols and APIs. Microsoft will ensure that these connections =
are open=20
      so that any developer can use them to connect to our products. We =
will=20
      provide open connections as follows:=20
      <TABLE class=3DnumberedList cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 =
border=3D0>
        <TBODY>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>1.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B><A =
href=3D"http://msdn.microsoft.com/openprotocols">Open=20
            Protocols.</A></B> Microsoft commits that all the protocols =
in its=20
            high-volume products that are used by any other Microsoft =
product=20
            will be made openly available to the developer community in =
a=20
            non-discriminatory fashion. These Open Protocols may include =

            protocols that implement industry standards. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>2.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Open APIs.</B> Microsoft commits that all the APIs in =
its=20
            high-volume products that are used by any other Microsoft =
product=20
            will be made openly available to the developer community in =
a=20
            non-discriminatory fashion. These Open APIs may include APIs =
that=20
            implement industry standards. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>3.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Open Access.</B> Microsoft will publish its =
documentation for=20
            these Open Protocols and Open APIs on its website so that =
all=20
            developers will have the benefit of this technical =
information in a=20
            manner that takes advantage of the nature of open discussion =
on the=20
            web. Microsoft will not require developers to obtain a =
license, or=20
            to pay a royalty or other fee, to have access to all this=20
            information. Under Principle IV, Microsoft will establish a =
forum=20
            that includes a mechanism for others to provide feedback and =

            commentary. This will foster the continued improvement of =
the=20
            documentation and facilitate third-party product =
development.=20
        </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>4.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>RAND Patent Terms.</B> Some of Microsoft=92s Open =
Protocols are=20
            covered by patents. Microsoft will indicate on its website =
which=20
            protocols are covered by Microsoft patents and will license =
all of=20
            these patents on reasonable and non-discriminatory terms, at =
low=20
            royalty rates. To assist developers in clearly understanding =
whether=20
            or not Microsoft patents may apply to any of the protocols,=20
            Microsoft will make available a list of the specific =
Microsoft=20
            patents and patent applications that cover each protocol. We =
will=20
            make this list available once for each release of a =
high-volume=20
            product that includes Open Protocols. Microsoft will not =
assert=20
            patents on any Open Protocol unless those patents appear on =
that=20
            list. Third parties do not need licenses to any Microsoft =
patents to=20
            call these Open APIs. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>5.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Open Source Compatibility.</B> Microsoft will <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/interop/principles/osspatentpledge.mspx"=
>covenant=20
            not to sue</A> open source developers for development and=20
            non-commercial distribution of implementations of these Open =

            Protocols. </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></P>
      <P><B>Principle II: Support for Standards</B><BR>Microsoft commits =
to=20
      supporting relevant standards in its high-volume products and =
doing so in=20
      a way that promotes interoperability. What this means is:=20
      <TABLE class=3DnumberedList cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 =
border=3D0>
        <TBODY>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>1.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Support for Key Standards.</B> Microsoft supports many =

            standards promulgated by standards bodies in its products =
today. We=20
            will rely upon customer advice emerging from our =
Interoperability=20
            Executive Customer Council and our ongoing community and =
customer=20
            engagement efforts to help us prioritize which standards we =
should=20
            support in any given product release. We will also continue =
to=20
            participate actively in standards bodies, contributing to =
the=20
            development of new standards and the improvement of existing =

            standards. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>2.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Broad Compatibility.</B> When the decision is made to =
support=20
            a standard in a version of a high-volume product, Microsoft =
will=20
            work with other major implementers of the standard toward =
achieving=20
            robust, consistent, and interoperable implementation across =
a broad=20
            range of widely deployed products. To that same end, =
Microsoft will=20
            document for the development community how it supports such=20
            standards and how it is working towards broad compatibility =
and=20
            interoperability. These steps will facilitate compatibility =
for=20
            customers in real-world scenarios. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>3.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Extensions.</B> Microsoft will document extensions to =
a=20
            standard implemented in its high-volume products where such=20
            extensions are relevant to interoperability with other=20
            implementations of that standard. Microsoft will publish the =

            extension specifications for the developer community on its =
website.=20
            In some cases Microsoft will also submit these extensions to =
the=20
            relevant standard-setting organization. These steps will =
enable=20
            developers who wish to do so to robustly interoperate with=20
            Microsoft=92s enhanced implementation of a standard.=20
      </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>As with its Open Protocols and Open =
APIs,=20
      Microsoft will publish information about its support for standards =
on its=20
      website, including the specifics of standards extensions, without=20
      requiring the developer to obtain a license, or to pay a royalty =
or other=20
      fee, to access such information. Microsoft will also make =
available a list=20
      of any of its patents that cover any extensions, and will make =
available=20
      patent licenses on reasonable and non-discriminatory terms. </P>
      <P><B>Principle III: Data Portability</B><BR>Once customers use =
one=20
      software product to store their data, they should be able to =
subsequently=20
      access that data in a form that permits its use in other software=20
      products. Microsoft commits to designing its high-volume products =
and=20
      providing documentation to enable such data portability. =
<BR><BR>There are=20
      a variety of means to achieve these goals. Microsoft will meet =
these goals=20
      through methods such as the following:=20
      <TABLE class=3DnumberedList cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 =
border=3D0>
        <TBODY>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>1.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Industry Standard Formats.</B> Microsoft supports many =
data=20
            formats promulgated by standards bodies in its products =
today. We=20
            will apply Principle II with respect to any standards-based =
data=20
            formats in our high-volume products. We will incorporate =
customer=20
            advice from our Interoperability Executive Customer Council =
and our=20
            ongoing community and customer engagement efforts to give us =

            guidance to prioritize which standards we support in any =
given=20
            product release. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>2.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Open Formats.</B> Any data formats developed by =
Microsoft=20
            where the portability and interchangeability of customer =
data is=20
            critical=97such as those formats in which users create and =
exchange=20
            documents=97will either be offered to a standard-setting =
organization=20
            for standardization, or will be made available to enable =
independent=20
            implementation by the developer community. Such Open Formats =
will be=20
            documented in their entirety with the exception of portions=20
            understood by the industry to be =93opaque by design,=94 =
such as objects=20
            embedded by other applications. Here again, access to =
specifications=20
            regarding Open Formats that are not standardized will be =
available=20
            on Microsoft=92s website, royalty-free, and with no need to =
obtain a=20
            license. Patents, if any apply, will be made available for =
licensing=20
            on reasonable and non-discriminatory terms. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>3.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Open Import/Export.</B> As another means to achieve =
data=20
            portability, Microsoft will provide =93import=94 and =
=93export=94 functions=20
            in various products that enable the transfer of user data =
from one=20
            application to another. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>4.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B>Document Format Defaults.</B> Different customers will =
choose=20
            different default document formats based on their own =
information=20
            management and retention needs. We will design the core =
Microsoft=20
            Office applications to enable customers to set default file =
formats=20
            they use when opening and saving documents. These =
applications will=20
            also include a plug-in architecture that enables developers =
to add=20
            support for opening and saving additional document formats.=20
        </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>Microsoft believes that the =
industry has a=20
      responsibility to come together to address the interests of users =
in=20
      interoperability and effective data exchange between widely =
deployed=20
      document format implementations. To this end, it will launch a =
Document=20
      Interoperability Initiative that will include an ongoing series of =
labs=20
      around the world where implementers of document formats optimize =
data=20
      exchange between implementations, community development of =
conformance=20
      testing suites for popular formats, and publication of document =
templates=20
      that enable optimized interoperability between different formats. =
</P>
      <P><B>Principle IV: Open Engagement</B><BR>Microsoft recognizes =
that no=20
      single company can address interoperability challenges on its own =
and that=20
      collaboration with customers, partners and other vendors is of =
critical=20
      importance. This collaboration includes open communication on the=20
      interoperability challenges that customers are experiencing and =
the ways=20
      in which those challenges can be addressed. In addition to our =
engagement=20
      under these principles with the Interoperability Executive =
Customer=20
      Council, Microsoft will increase our communications with the =
customer,=20
      information technology, and open source communities. What this =
means is:=20
      <TABLE class=3DnumberedList cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 =
border=3D0>
        <TBODY>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>1.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/interop/principles/forum.mspx">Interoper=
ability=20
            Forum.</A></B> Microsoft will create an Interoperability =
Forum for=20
            discussing and addressing interoperability related issues of =

            importance to customers around the world. The =
Interoperability Forum=20
            will be an easy to use, web-based resource containing =
information=20
            about what Microsoft is doing in the area of =
interoperability, and=20
            will enable an open dialogue on issues of importance to =
users and=20
            information technology companies. Microsoft will continue to =
work=20
            through the Interoperability Vendor Alliance and other =
industry=20
            mechanisms to collaborate on the development of solutions to =
those=20
            issues. </P></TD></TR>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD class=3DlistNumber noWrap align=3Dright>
            <P>2.</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P><B><A =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/opensource/interop">Open=20
            Source Interoperability Initiative.</A></B> To increase=20
            interoperability with open source solutions, the Microsoft =
Open=20
            Source Interoperability Initiative will facilitate bilateral =

            engagement between Microsoft and the open source community. =
This=20
            initiative will encompass a broad range of facilities, =
events, and=20
            resources supporting interoperability, including labs, =
=93plug fests,=94=20
            and technical content, as well as opportunities for =
participation in=20
            ongoing cooperative development. =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>Developers=20
      may be interested in access to additional Microsoft technologies =
beyond=20
      those covered in these principles. Microsoft is open to discussing =
how=20
      additional technology sharing could provide customer benefits in=20
      particular scenarios with a view toward licensing its intellectual =

      property on commercially reasonable terms. </P>
      <P>See also: <BR><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/presskits/interoperability/def=
ault.mspx">Press=20
      Information</A><BR><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/interop/principles/forum.mspx">Interoper=
ability=20
      Forum</A><BR><A =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/opensource/interop">Open=20
      Source Interoperability Initiative </A><BR><A=20
      href=3D"http://msdn.microsoft.com/openprotocols">Open Protocols=20
      Documentation</A></P><BR style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 0pt" clear=3Dall>
